metadata.name: Eikonal identities #173
metadata.description:
Works in the invisible
Inevitable shadows
Digital exorcism
Silicon catharsis


Eikonal
- Usually "eikonal equation" : the wave-like description of the propagation of light through a medium
- In optics, relative to the formation of an image
- anagram : e-kaolin



-----
* What/How *

Product of the code.

A picture generated by a succession of chaotic events applied to a system of 4.2 million particles.
The drawing process consists of mixing and projecting the particles randomly in space.

Each image is unique and depends only on the address of minter's wallet and current iteration number.

-----
* Technics *

- Hand written code in Javascript, GLSL
- Uses three.js library, WebGL particles, physics
- Generates a FullHD PNG (1080x1080 px bitmap 24bits)
- Takes less than 15 seconds of generation on a relatively recent GPU (>2017)

-----
@HAL09999 – August 8th, 2023
https://twitter.com/HAL09999
https://instagram.com/hal09999
https://danslesnuages.xyz

metadata.name: Paysages Chromatiques A #124
metadata.description:
Taking my inspiration from impressionist and contemporary paintings, I tried to generate 
mixtures of more or less superimposed colors, creating flowing effects or spots as one
would obtain with paint.
This work is the first in a two-part series featuring abstraction and imagination.
I hope it will inspire you to take the time to daydream, or simply to spend a moment 
where the mind can wander freely through the colors.

To save a png file type [s]
TO remove the texture type [t]

To render at higher resolution add &pd=2 at the end of the url in live mode
(others values are valid too but be patient the rendering can be long)
---
100% code made with p5js and glsl
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.
---
Hervé (23 nov)

metadata.name: Plottable Mountain Moons #591
metadata.description:
What makes this NFT have value? not only the digital is cool but it is the recipe to a plottable. Owning this NFT confers the right to request a physical plot (21cm square). @greweb will ask extra fees for this service => https://greweb.me/plots/nft

Full article: https://greweb.me/2021/12/plottable-mountain-moons

Plottable Mountain Moons generalize many explorations done this year. There are 13 inks, 9 different shape primitives with recursion, various intensity, and frequencies of noise,... and many rare cases to discover!

Digital and Physical art, hybrid and decoupled:
- The art is published via a digital NFT on Tezos blockchain – its digital representation simulates fountain pen inks drawing on paper with animated effects.
- Token to the physical world: owning each NFT confer the power to request the related physical plot: https://greweb.me/plots/nft

@greweb – 2021 – tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM – CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: this is a bird #37
metadata.description:
"Imagine an infant lying in its cradle and the window is open and into the room comes something marvelous, mysterious, glittering, shedding light of many colors, movement, sound, a transformative hierophany of integrated perception... and the child is enthralled.

And then the mother comes into the room and she says to the child 'That's a bird, baby. That's a bird.' Instantly, the complex wave of the angel peacock iridescent transformative mystery is collapsed into the word. All mystery is gone.

The child learns 'this is a bird, this is a bird'. And by the time we’re five or six years old all the mystery of reality has been carefully tiled over with words."
-- Terence McKenna

metadata.name: Hashway 69 Revisited #22
metadata.description:
'Hashway 69 Revisited' by pixelwank
Following on from BlockonBlock, this is the evolution of that concept. 

Whether you're a Dylan or a Degen, the Hashies are for everyone. 

These give me feelings of warmth and hope or isolation & loneliness - depending on the output or my headspace at the time of viewing. 

These include a bunch of variables including:
- 23 colour palettes 
- 'dusk' or 'day' colour overlays 
- roads (%80), train tracks(15%) or paths(5%)
- clouds
- windows on the buildings & number of buildings 
- mountains 
- grasses & pond 
- moon/sun & sky texture 
& more... 

Click the image or press 's' or 'S' in live move for a 3000x3000 png 
Can look into doing even more hi-res copies for collectors in the future (I think!)

Also apologies for long loading time, my coding will get better! hehe 

This is somewhat of a culmination of the last few months learning and digging into p5js & generative art and I'm super proud of these. Thanks for collecting.
Big shoutout to all the frens at Circolors for the love and support. 
Also big shoutout to the FxHash community for being so welcoming & supportive.

R.I.F.F.
Remember It's For Fun

metadata.name: Einstein-Rosen Memories #38
metadata.description:
At first this was 'just' an attempt at visualizing my childhood imagination of wormholes.
As I worked on the code and the more the fusion of music and visuals took me over, the more this piece led me to deeper thoughts.
How vague can something be in order to really exist?

Well, this, of course raised many new questions.
Questions about space-time, about metaphysical assumptions, about the transmission of thoughts and feelings and so on.

The longer you ask yourself about these things, the more the boundary between fiction and reality becomes blurred, because there really is none.

///
Click for audio.
png screenshot: 's' in live view (I highly recommend doing this!).

No rarity features this time, your taste decides.
The music was written and recorded on December 15th, 2020 on a Tascam 4-track tape recorder. 

PLEASE NOTE:
The thumbnails do not reflect the actual artwork.
(See them as another layer of vague memories)

metadata.name: Pegs In Motion #151
metadata.description:
Pegs In Motion adds a twist to the original PEGS project by adding animation, rotating the pegs to make the string loop around the grid and bring the artwork alive. Forever limited to 500 unique editions on the Tezos blockchain.

Taking inspiration from work by Karl Gerstner, Armin Hofmann, Nick Kuder and Dmitri Cherniak, Pegs In Motion explores the limits of constrained algorithmic variation. Based on the simple, playful idea of wrapping a string across a board of pegs, it shows how endless possibilities can be achieved with just a basic set of rules and a few primary colors. When done right, generative art challenges us to answer fundamental questions around creativity, beauty, and life itself.
